Why rightmost of left subtree?
Because it is the largest element smaller than the deleted node.

BST property remains valid.
all left < root < all right
The rightmost node of left subtree is already the maximum among smaller values.
The key observation, bestie, is that we don't actually delete by swapping values (the common recursive approach). Striver's solution 
physically reconnects subtrees, which makes the logic very clean once you understand:
"Take the left subtree, find its largest node, attach the right subtree there, and return the left subtree."

Everything else is just BST search to reach the node



class Solution {
public:
   TreeNode* findRightMost(TreeNode* root){
    while(root){
        root = root->right;
    }
    return root;
   }
       TreeNode* helper(TreeNode* root){
        if(root->left == NULL){
            root = root->right;
        }
        if(root-right==NULL){
